#Histogram of Petal Width with 10 bins

          main="Grade First Semerter",

          main="Grade Second Semester",
          xlab="Grade")

          main="Overall grade",

          main="Age",
          xlab="Age")

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

Barplot

Since we have a lot of columns with defined variables, it is interesting to make some barplots so we can get a better uderstanding of the dataset.

Data Analysis

Hypothesis Testing

alcohol <- data[c('age','failures', 'sex', 'G2', 'G3', 'Dalc', 'Walc', 'studytime', 'failures', 'goout')]
str(alcohol)
## 'data.frame':    395 obs. of  10 variables:

##  $ failures  : int  0 0 3 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 ...

Effect of alcohol on grades

h0: Mean of grade of people who drink more = Mean of grade of people who drink less h1: Mean of people who drink more != Mean of people who drink less

less <- alcohol[alcohol['Walc'] < 3,]
more <- alcohol[alcohol['Walc'] > 2,]
t.test(more$G3, less$G3)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  more$G3 and less$G3
## t = -0.47396, df = 389.38, p-value = 0.6358
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.0846814  0.6632977
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  10.28931  10.50000

Effect of study time on grades

h0: Mean of grades of people who study more = Mean of grades of people who study less h1: Mean of grades of people who study more != Mean of grades of people who study less

t.test(more$G3, less$G3)

Relation between failure and drinking

h0: Mean of alcohol of people who fail more = Mean of alcohol of people who fail less h1: Mean of alcohol of people who fail more != Mean of alcohol of people who fail less

less <- alcohol[alcohol['failures'] < 3,]
more <- alcohol[alcohol['failures'] > 2,]
t.test(more$Walc, less$Walc)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  more$Walc and less$Walc
## t = 1.5742, df = 15.714, p-value = 0.1354
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2348536  1.5821491
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  2.937500  2.263852

Relation between gender and drinking

h0: Mean of alcohol of woman = Mean of alcohol of men h1: Mean of alcohol of woman != Mean of alcohol of men

female <- alcohol[alcohol['sex'] == 'F',]
male <- alcohol[alcohol['sex'] == 'M',]
t.test(female$Walc, male$Walc)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  female$Walc and male$Walc
## t = -5.5666, df = 341.41, p-value = 5.263e-08

## mean of x mean of y 
##  1.956731  2.663102

Linear regression model

Forward Stepwise

# Create a null model 
intercept_only <- lm(G3 ~ 1, data=data)
# Create a full model
all <- lm(G3~., data=data)
# perform forward step-wise regression
forward <- stepAIC (intercept_only, direction='forward',scope = formula(all))
